image.altText: Flooding covers most of the town of Huonville

props.synopsis: Tasmania's hydroelectric operator says it did not want to "create unnecessary concern" for residents of a small town by releasing flood mapping, done in 2016, which shows what could happen should a rare earthquake event cause catastrophic failure of two dams —  now with the maps public, the utility says there "no need" to be worried.

title.children: Two dams sit on a fault line with a Tasmanian town downstream. The flood risk was kept from residents for years

image.altText: Aerial shot of massive oil and gas rig in the Bass Strait off Victoria

props.synopsis: Offshore gas supplies are running out in the Bass Strait and there are plans to dismantle some of Esso's ocean gas rigs. But the company's intention to leave parts of them in the sea has sparked concerns.

title.children: Mercury and asbestos are in decommissioned Bass Strait gas rigs. A fight is brewing over their removal

image.altText: Kirsha Kaechele with fake picasso

props.synopsis: The news that supposed Picasso artworks at Tasmania's Museum of Old and New Art were fakes painted by a local artist has drawn a mixed response, with some describing it a damaging to the gallery's credibility — while others have lauded it as a publicity masterstroke.

title.children: 'Brilliant', 'confusing', 'typical Kirsha': Faked Picasso ruse another publicity coup for Mona

image.altText: Shelley Duvall with short blonde hair and a fringe smiles at the camera wearing a red shirt

props.synopsis: Shelley Duvall — a regular star in some of the defining movies of the 1970s and 1980s — dies decades after retreating from the spotlight and settling in a small town in Texas.

title.children: Shelley Duvall — star of The Shining and a regular in Robert Altman films — dies aged 75

image.altText: Joe Biden waves at the camera, looking serious, the NATO logo is imprinted on the wall behind him

props.synopsis: US President Joe Biden is set to speak at a solo press conference at the White House, two weeks to the day after his disastrous debate performance against Donald Trump. Follow live.

title.children: Joe Biden to hold rare press conference as campaign pressure builds

image.altText: Woman wearing an Akubra hat in selfie

props.synopsis: Call for the mandatory return of income support management has some on the edge of tears and fears people could leave towns to avoid the reintroduction.

title.children: 'Don't think we'd survive it': Anxieties that Morrison-era policy could return amid cost-of-living crisis

image.altText: Richard Marles and Joe Biden shake hands.

props.synopsis: The Australian government is set to give Ukraine another $250 million in military support — its largest contribution to the war effort to date.

title.children: Australia pledges biggest ever boost for Ukraine as NATO calls out China as Russia's 'enabler'

props.synopsis: South Korea promotes closer defence ties as it seeks to win a lucrative contract to deliver the Royal Australian Navy’s new fleet of frigates.

title.children: South Korea pushes Australia on AUKUS, cyber cooperation as it eyes $10b warship prize

props.synopsis: A look into the transformative journey of Japanese anime from World War II propaganda reels to today's billion-dollar, Pokemon-filled world.

title.children: ‘For us kids, we didn’t see Japan that way’: From military empire to land of fantasy and dreams

image.altText: Jen Daine stands under two bridges and looks up into the distrance.

props.synopsis: Commercial photographer Jen Dainer was applying for the Army Reserve when a question about the date of her last period stopped her in her tracks. A Department of Defence spokesperson said the content of the questionnaire is being revised.

title.children: 'Like asking a man what his sperm count is': Should the ADF ask applicants about their periods?

image.altText: Ed John. Executive Manager, Stewardship at the Melbourne office in July 2022.

props.synopsis: CEO bonuses are becoming a "given" according to a long-running study, despite a rise in investor strikes against remuneration reports.

title.children: Corporate governance experts urge moderation in CEO bonus pay

image.altText: A drawing of a mammoth surrounded by tusks and bones

props.synopsis: An incredibly well-preserved woolly mammoth specimen that died 52,000 years ago in Siberia has now had its chromosome structure reassembled for the first time.

title.children: First ancient chromosomes reconstructed from 52,000-year-old woolly mammoth

image.altText: The outside of a hotel

props.synopsis: An Australian couple have been murdered at a luxury hotel in the Philippines, police officials say.

title.children: Australian couple found dead at luxury Philippines hotel

image.altText: made in australia logo

props.synopsis: Senior Labor ministers are accused of "ripping off" an iconic logo used to promote Australian-made products.

title.children: Sussan Ley accuses Labor of 'ripping off' Australia Made logo to promote flagship policy

image.altText: An 18th century painting of an African American man in a suit

props.synopsis: Firsthand accounts of slavery in the US are extremely rare. But this American academic made a remarkable discovery in an online Australian database.

title.children: This fugitive American slave ended up in Australia. Now his story can be told

image.altText: NT Chief Minister Eva Lawler holds a press conference in front of several journalists.

props.synopsis: The NT government says its curfew laws have been triggered “for the safety of people in Alice Springs”. But ahead of an election, some say it smacks of politics.

title.children: ‘Nothing but politics’: Alice Springs curfew raises questions over NT government influence

image.altText: A photo of Gymnastics coach Jeb Silsbury. He is smiling in the photo

props.synopsis: An Australian gymnastics coach selected for the Paris Olympics is accused of making comments about a former colleague's breasts and calling her a "minion".

title.children: Gymnastics coach withdraws from Olympics after allegations of inappropriate behaviour raised

image.altText: A young couple pose, the man has his arm around the woman's waist

props.synopsis: A quarter of Australia's homeless are young people. While Chloe Hume and Trent Kiely are among them, a caravan by a river has offered them refuge from housing stress.

title.children: Young couple find shelter in a caravan after being left homeless in cut-throat rental market

image.altText: An older man in a suit and red, spotted tie, speaks into a microphone on a podium during an address.

props.synopsis: Labor's Don Farrell is working on changes that would cap both donations and spending during federal elections. But the far-reaching reforms are expected to face a rough parliamentary road ahead.

title.children: Inside the reform battle aiming to protect Australia from 'billionaires who try to influence our elections'

image.altText: A man stands in front of a solar battery system.

props.synopsis: Jon Coffey wants to install a battery system so he can store the solar power output when he's not at home — but he says he's "looking at nearly $20,000" to fund it.

title.children: Jon wants to capture solar energy when he's not at home. But battery systems don't come cheap

image.altText: A row of large white tanks that each read "Cryonics Institute" in a line

props.synopsis: Figuring out how to bring humans back to life is just part of the challenge of cryonics. A reanimated person could also face huge psychological, legal, and financial obstacles in a whole new world.

title.children: Scientists don't know how to stop frozen humans becoming a 'goopy mess', but there are more questions about cryonics

image.altText: Carl King and his mother embrace.

props.synopsis: Bundjalung man Carl King says as a child he fell in with a troubled crowd, and later suffered the grief of his brother's death. But community-focused boxing has helped him stay grounded and "out of trouble".

title.children: From childhood behavioural issues to the loss of his brother, boxing is how Carl stays grounded

image.altText: A woman in a fluro vest stands on a ladder stacking books on shelves.

props.synopsis: Booktopia's collapse has rocked an industry that was already financially on thin ice, so what will fill the giant hole left by its collapse?

title.children: What the collapse of a major book retailer tells us about the state of Australian publishing

image.altText: A black and white dairy cow looks up from its trough of feed

props.synopsis: One of Australia's most expensive environmental policies is changing the way water and land are used to grow our crops and tend to livestock. This is how the Murray-Darling Basin Plan has triggered a mega shift in farmers' thinking.

image.altText: A woman holds a mobile phone while waiting to cross the road in Brisbane's CBD.

props.synopsis: If you've got a phone, it's likely you've been on the receiving end of more than a few scam text messages or calls.

title.children: Scammers are using our scam awareness against us

image.altText: A man and woman smiling

props.synopsis: Lynn Maney has been training and racing greyhounds for more than 50 years, and says the industry has "improved enormously" in the past decade despite a report released this week from the former NSW head vet which claims there is widespread animal abuse.

title.children: 'It's just a way of life': Greyhound trainers in NSW insist the industry has improved despite damning report from former head vet

image.altText: A woman wearing a purple shirt roars with two people celebrating behind her

props.synopsis: Instead of re-signing for her English club West Ham, the Matildas goalkeeper has returned to America's NWSL. But why?

title.children: Does Mackenzie Arnold's NWSL move signal a turning tide in women's football?

image.altText: The court logo on the Melbourne Magistrates' Court.

props.synopsis: Michael Stanyer breached consumer law and called debtors "dickheads" and "pathetic lying losers", then told a magistrate he won't be paying his fine.

title.children: Debt collector who refuses to pay fine faces five-year ban over harassing calls

image.altText: An Aboriginal woman gazes into the distance

title.children: Anti-violence campaigner says government must listen to 'voices from the bush' after Alice Springs curfew

image.altText: A woman stands in front of a wall in Kyiv. Behind the wall there appears to be a timber baricade

props.synopsis: Yulia was filming on her phone in Kyiv when a nearby children's hospital was struck by a Russian missile. She says it "literally looked like Armageddon".

title.children: 'Like Armageddon': Kyiv resident recalls moment children's hospital was hit

image.altText: An older man in a suit with a bright red cap gestures as he speaks behind a lectern.

props.synopsis: The implications for what happens next in the race for the White House have ramifications that stretch far beyond US shores. And that's a key reason why Australia and China are closely watching what happens next.

title.children: Trump says he could end the Russia-Ukraine war 'within a day'. It's enough to send shivers down Australia's spine

image.altText: Side portrait of woman with pink and purple hair, wearing a leopard print top.

props.synopsis: Over 13 years NSW authorities received 56 reports about the welfare of Sally. She wants her story to be heard so no other little girl suffers in the same way.

title.children: Abused since age 3, it took more than 50 departmental reports and 10 years to remove Sally from that home

image.altText: Two police officers in tactical gear stand on a street with their backs to the camera

props.synopsis: A magistrate deals a fresh blow to a "weak" Commonwealth case against a suspected Sydney terrorism network, describing an alleged terror plan as "all talk" as he grants bail to a fourth teenager.

title.children: 'All talk': Court grants bail to another alleged terror plotter, branding Crown case 'weak'

image.altText: Joe Biden speaks at a podium with two microphones and points straight ahead. A door and flag are behind him.

props.synopsis: Fist fights broke out the last time the Democratic Party's presidential candidate was decided on the convention floor in 1968.

title.children: If President Joe Biden drops out of the race, what happens next?

image.altText: Upwards shot of the BHP building in Perth.

props.synopsis: Mining giant BHP has announced it’s putting its WA nickel mines on ice for at least three years, blaming an "oversupply in the global nickel market."

title.children: Redundancies and redeployments on offer for 1,600 people as BHP shuts nickel mines
